DOCUMENT();        # This should be the first executable line in the problem.

loadMacros("PG.pl",
           "PGbasicmacros.pl",
           "PGchoicemacros.pl",
           "PGanswermacros.pl",
           "PGauxiliaryFunctions.pl",
		"extraAnswerEvaluators.pl");


$r1 = random(-9,-1,2);
$r2 = random(2,8,2);

while( ($r1+$r2)**2 == 1 )
{
    $r2 = random(1,9,2);
}
$b = ($r1 + $r2);
$c = -$r1*$r2;


TEXT(beginproblem());

$showPartialCorrectAnswers = 1;



TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));
Let
\[ f(x) = $c ? {$b} x - x^2.  \]
$BR
(A) Use interval notation to indicate where \( f(x) \) is increasing.
$PAR
$PAR
{\bf Note:} When using interval notation in WeBWorK, remember
that:
\begin{itemize}
\item You use 'I' for \(\infty\) and '-I' for \(-\infty\).
\item 'U' for the union symbol.
\item If you have extra boxes, fill each in with an 'x'.
\end{itemize}

Increasing:
$BR
\{ans_rule(25)\}
$PAR
$PAR
EOT

@answers = (interval_cmp("(-I,$b/2)"));

ANS( @answers );

TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));
$BR
(B) Use interval notation to indicate where \( f(x) \) is decreasing.
$PAR
Decreasing:
$BR
\{ans_rule(25)\}
$PAR
$PAR
EOT

@answers = (interval_cmp("($b/2,I)"));


ANS( @answers );

TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));
$BR
(C) Find the average of the \(x\) values of all local maxima of
\(f\).
$BR
Note: If there are no local maxima, enter -1000.
$PAR
Average of \(x\) values = \{ans_rule(7)\}
$PAR
$PAR
EOT

@answers = (num_cmp($b/2) );

ANS( @answers );

TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));
$BR
(D) Find the average of the \(x\) values of all local minima of
\(f\).
$BR
Note: If there are no local minima, enter -1000.
$PAR
Average of \(x\) values = \{ans_rule(7)\}
$PAR
$PAR
EOT

@answers = (num_cmp(-1000) );

ANS( @answers );

TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));
$BR
(E) Use the preceding information to sketch a
graph of \(f\).  When you're finished, enter a "1" in the box
below.
$BR
$BR
Graph Complete: \{ans_rule(12)\}
$PAR
$PAR
EOT

@answers = (num_cmp(1) );

ANS( @answers );

ENDDOCUMENT();        # This should be the last executable line in the problem.
